snippet.textDisplay:
Sindhiyun je ain lateef sain je kalam ji hin behtareen peshkash lai sawan khan ain saji team ja lakh thora 🙏... 
There are such legendary love stories from sindhi folk literature and shah latif and others have colored them in sufi colors and immortalised the surmis (heroines).... We have content and we also have so many talented Sindhi Fimmakers in our country (Anand L Rai, Ram Madhvani, Sippy brothers etc.)...Hope one day we can see any one sindhi love tale like sasui punhu, umar marui, leela chanesar Or mumal rano immortalised on celluloid like SLB's masterpiece Bajirao mastani.

snippet.textDisplay:
Story of the intro is wrong, Sassi live in Banbhore where as Punhoon was a prince from persia who came to Banbhore (Ancient port of Daibal) he was selling perfumes, girld came to his stall when sassi saw Punhoon and Punhoon saw sassi it was live at first sight Punhoon became a washerman to marry Sassi while the fither from Iran knew about this he sent the brothers of Punhoon to bring back Punhoon but they couldnt convice hin finally they played a trick on wedding day they distributed wine from persia which had some sleeping medicine the whole village slept so did Sassui they took punhoon on back of camels to Persia. Next morning when sassui  got up her city became Banbhore (Broken to dust) so she also walked to persia in between was the Balouchistan desert when her feet were woonded her clothes ton and sun was setting she prayed to mountain (Doongar) do not grieve as I am just about to end journey.
Philosophically, Doongar is god and so is the Punhoon and Sassui is humankind who is searching god
